snippet.textDisplay: Hey Julien! You really did it to em today. Alton brown has a recipe for brûléed grapefruit with flakes salt on top of the sugar crust. You might enjoy making it.   Also—the mixture is hot out of the blender because the kinetic energy of movement and friction is getting transformed into heat. Also if you let the mixture actually come to a simmer and then keep that level of heat for a minute, it might better activate the thickening properties of the arrowroot flour.
snippet.textOriginal: Hey Julien! You really did it to em today. Alton brown has a recipe for brûléed grapefruit with flakes salt on top of the sugar crust. You might enjoy making it. He told us all the story the third day he was our sub. He was an awesome little old man who at the age of 81 climbed to the first checkpoint on mount everest. Like that man had more energy then me. I loved that man and hes the reason we have creme brulee in america today.

snippet.textDisplay: Hey Julien, greetings from Spain! Loved your video (actually I love all of them). There is a Spanish dish that I'm sure you will love, it is called "croquetas". Traditionally they are made with ham but the veggie version with boletus is AMAZING. This link is basically an example of what croquetas are (a ball of bechamel with mushrooms breaded and fried). I'm sure it is possible to make them vegan. https://www.google.com/search?q=croqueta+de+boletus&client=ms-android-xiaomi-rev1&prmd=ivmn&sxsrf=ALeKk02U8Zg8O4zm6mPW70-1gibbB-yRmQ:1582490711064&source=lnms&tbm=isch&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi6wsWlxejnAhUGtosKHRqJDa0Q_AUoAXoECA0QAQ&biw=393&bih=702#imgrc=2UfHZMlna-G9pM&imgdii=MNznq_jyR6VpIM
